Event Name: COVID-19 Community Vaccination Event at Khalsa Gurmat Center
Event description/details:
Walk Up Only Event

When: Sunday September 18, 2022 from 10am to 2pm

Where: Khalsa Gurmat Center in Federal Way

Vaccine Available(s): Pfizer, Moderna, Pediatric Doses for Ages 6 months and older

Partner(s): Khalsa Gurmat Center

Indoor/Outdoor: Outdoors

We are serving community members on a first come, first served basis. Vaccine supply is limited and we cannot guarantee that everyone who walks in will be able to receive a vaccine.

Vaccine(s) are FREE to everyone, regardless of your income, insurance, citizenship, or immigration status.

The U.S. Food and Drug Administration has limited the authorized use of the Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine (J&J Vaccine). Limited supply of Janssen will be available at community pop-up events for individuals 18 years of age and older for whom other authorized or approved COVID-19 vaccines are not accessible or clinically appropriate. We strongly encourage individuals 18 years of age and older to elect Moderna or Pfizer for their primary vaccination series or for their booster doses.

Masks and social distancing must be followed at all pop-up events. See current guidelines at https://kingcounty.gov/depts/health/covid-19/current-guidance.aspx.

If you have a disability and need reasonable ADA accommodation(s), these are available by request. Call 206.477.3977, 8am to 7pm (interpreters available) or email publichealthaccommodations@kingcounty.gov. Note that if Public Health cannot assist with disability accommodations for the community pop-up event, we will instead help to make an appointment at a separate, accessible King County vaccination site.

For language interpretation, call 206.477.3977, 8am to 7pm. (Say your preferred language in English when connected).

Event Name: COVID-19 Vaccination Pop-up at the Seattle Children's Theatre
Event description/details:
Get your COVID19 Vaccine right at Seattle Children’s Theatre! In collaboration with Seattle Children's Museum, Discovery Health MD will provide Pfizer and Moderna vaccinations for infants, children, and adults at SCT. Pre-register for an appointment using the infant and/or child & adult links below!


Register for an Infant Pfizer/Moderna (6mo - 5yr) dose:https://prepmod.doh.wa.gov//appointment/en/reg/9786801992

Register for an Adult and/or Pediatric Pfizer/Moderna dose:https://prepmod.doh.wa.gov//appointment/en/reg/8926408129


Pre-registering is strongly encouraged for people to secure their appointments; doses are limited. Street parking is available – but leave plenty of time to find parking and arrive.


A voucher for FREE ADMISSION to Seattle Children’s theater will be offered with each vaccination!


Masks and social distancing must be followed at all pop-up events. See current guidelines at https://kingcounty.gov/depts/health/covid-19/current-guidance.aspx.

Event Name: Back to School Vaccination Pop-up Event
Event description/details:
Families, get students caught up on all required vaccines before the first day of school! In partnership with Seattle Children’s Hospital and Odessa Brown Clinic, SPS is offing a vaccine clinic to offer all vaccines required for K-12 school entry, including Tdap, DTaP, MMR, hepatitis B, varicella, and polio. In addition, free COVID-19, HPV, and meningococcal vaccines will be available for children up to age 18.


Place: John Stanford Center for Educational Excellence 2445 3rd Ave S., in the lobby

Vaccine provider: Seattle Children’s Hospital/Odessa Brown Children’s Clinic

Who: Children ages 0 to 18

Insurance: Accepted, not required to receive free vaccines. No child will be turned away due to lack of insurance or their immigration status.

Legal parent or guardian must be present.

If you have a disability and need reasonable ADA accommodation(s), these are available by request. Call 206.477.3977, 8am to 5pm (interpreters available) or email publichealthaccommodations@kingcounty.gov. Note that if Public Health cannot assist with disability accommodations for the community pop-up event, we will instead help to make an appointment at a separate, accessible King County vaccination site.

Masks and social distancing must be followed at all pop-up events. See current guidelines at https://kingcounty.gov/depts/health/covid-19/current-guidance.aspx.

Event Name: COVID-19 Community Vaccination Event at Seattle Children’s Theatre
Event description/details:
Get your COVID19 Vaccine right at Seattle Children’s Theatre! In collaboration with Seattle Children's Museum, Discovery Health MD will provide Pfizer and Moderna vaccinations for infants, children, and adults at SCT on Sunday, August 7 from 10 am - 2 pm. Pre-register for an appointment using the infant and/or child & adult links below!

Register for an Infant Pfizer/Moderna (6mo - 5yr) dose: https://prepmod.doh.wa.gov//appointment/en/reg/9617329008

Register for an Adult and/or Pediatric Pfizer/Moderna dose: https://prepmod.doh.wa.gov//appointment/en/reg/8069960321

Pre-registering is strongly encouraged for people to secure their appointments. Doses are limited: up to 48 for infants and up to 75 for children over 5 years-adults. But if appointments are still available, they will take walk-ups. Street parking is available – but leave plenty of time to find parking and arrive.

A voucher for FREE ADMISSION to Seattle Children’s theater will be offered with each vaccination!

Event Name: COVID-19 Vaccination Pop-up with Renegades for Life
Event description/details:
Walk Up Only Event

When: Friday, July 1, 2022, 1:00PM-4:00PM 

Where: 1046 S Jackson St. Seattle 98144

Vaccine Available(s): Pfizer, Moderna, J&J 

Partner(s): Renegades for Life 

Indoor/Outdoor: Outdoor 

We are serving community members on a first come, first served basis. Vaccine supply is limited and we cannot guarantee that everyone who walks in will be able to receive a vaccine.

Vaccine(s) are FREE to everyone age 5 and up, regardless of your income, insurance, citizenship, or immigration status.

Children, Ages 5-17 can get Pfizer ONLY and must be accompanied by a parent or legal guardian.

The U.S. Food and Drug Administration has limited the authorized use of the Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine (J&J Vaccine). Limited supply of Janssen will be available at community pop-up events for individuals 18 years of age and older for whom other authorized or approved COVID-19 vaccines are not accessible or clinically appropriate. We strongly encourage individuals 18 years of age and older to elect Moderna or Pfizer for their primary vaccination series or for their boosters doses.

Masks and social distancing must be followed at all pop-up events. See current guidelines at https://kingcounty.gov/depts/health/covid-19/current-guidance.aspx.

If you have a disability and need reasonable ADA accommodation(s), these are available by request. Call 206.477.3977, 8am to 7pm (interpreters available) or email publichealthaccommodations@kingcounty.gov. Note that if Public Health cannot assist with disability accommodations for the community pop-up event, we will instead help to make an appointment at a separate, accessible King County vaccination site.

For language interpretation, call 206.477.3977, 8am to 7pm. (Say your preferred language in English when connected).

When: Tuesday, February 15, 8:30AM - 11:30AM

Where: Enumclaw Public Library - 1700 1st Street, Enumclaw, WA 98022

Vaccine Available(s): Pfizer, Moderna, Johnson and Johnson, Pediatric Doses

Partner(s): King County Library System

Indoor/Outdoor: Indoor

We are serving community members on a first come, first served basis. Vaccine supply is limited and we cannot guarantee that everyone who walks in will be able to receive a vaccine.

Vaccine(s) are FREE to everyone age 5 and up, regardless of your income, insurance, citizenship, or immigration status.

Children, Ages 5-17 can get Pfizer ONLY and must be accompanied by a parent or legal guardian.

Masks and social distancing must be followed at all pop-up events. See current guidelines at https://kingcounty.gov/depts/health/covid-19/current-guidance.aspx.

Free rides to and from vaccination events and appointments are available. Call 425-943-6706 or go to bit.ly/vaxride.

If you have a disability and need reasonable ADA accommodation(s), these are available by request. Call 206.477.3977, 8am to 7pm (interpreters available) or email publichealthaccommodations@kingcounty.gov. Note that if Public Health cannot assist with disability accommodations for the community pop-up event, we will instead help to make an appointment at a separate, accessible King County vaccination site.

For language interpretation, call 206.477.3977, 8am to 7pm. (Say your preferred language in English when connected).

When: Tuesday, November 2, 8:30 AM - 4:00 PM

Where: Navos Mental Health and Wellness Center - 1210 SW 136th St, Burien, WA 98166

Vaccine Available(s): Pfizer, Moderna, Johnson & Johnson

Partner(s): PHSKC - Navos Health Mammogram van

Please Note:

Walk-ups welcome. No appointment needed.

Vaccine(s) are FREE to everyone age 12 and up, regardless of your income, insurance, citizenship, or immigration status.

Children, Ages 12-17 can get Pfizer ONLY and must be accompanied by a parent or legal guardian.

Vaccine shots & recovery time take approximately 20 minutes.

Free rides to and from events and appointments are available. Call 425-943-6706 or go to, bit.ly/vaxride.

If you have a disability and need reasonable ADA accommodation(s) available by request. Call 206.477.3977, 8am to 7pm (interpreters available) or email publichealthaccommodations@kingcounty.gov.

For language interpretation, call 206.477.3977, 8am to 7pm. (Say your preferred language in English when connected).

* Drop-in COVID-19 booster shots are available for eligible adults, age 18 and up, at all of our King County vaccination sites (no appointment needed). For a list of sites, go to: kingcounty.gov/vaccine. For more information about booster eligibility, go to: bit.ly/CDC-VaxBoosters

* A third dose of the Pfizer or Moderna COVID-19 vaccine is only for people with significantly compromised immune systems. The new recommendation does not apply to people who got the J&J vaccine. For more info, go to bit.ly/third-dose.
Location name: Navos Mental Health and Wellness Center

Event Name: COVID-19 Vaccination Pop-up at Washington Elementary
Event description/details:
The Alliance of People with disAbilities, in partnership with Public Health Seattle King County, the Seattle Cancer Care Alliance, and the Auburn School District is hosting a fully accessible and inclusive vaccination clinic for youth with disabilities (12+).

When: Saturday, June 5 10AM-1PM

Where: Washington Elementary, 20 E St NE, Auburn WA

Who: This event has been specifically tailored and designed for:

  • People with disabilities (12+)
  • Family members of people with disabilities
  • Caregivers

Translation Services: ASL & Deaf-Blind Interpreters are available to be on-site if there is a need. Please indicate if you have this need in your registration.

Accommodations/Other Services: In-car vaccinations are available for people who have difficulty ambulating, easy access to seating in all areas of the clinic, low-sensory clinic, fidget/sensory items available, space to pace/walk, volunteers trained in the communication/behavioral needs of people with disabilities. Spoken language interpreters available upon request.

This clinic will be distributing first dose vaccinations of Pfizer. Parental consent is required for vaccination of a minor. Second dose appointments will be scheduled at the clinic for June 26.

QUESTIONS? Please contact kayla@disabilitypride.org

Free Disaster Skills Workshop
Event description/details:
King County is prone to many hazards, and when one happens many services we rely on will be overwhelmed. It may be difficult for residents to travel or communicate. Residents need to be prepared to be self-sufficient during these times. Understanding of disaster skills is critical to being prepared.

Our free workshop will provide an overview on hazards and certain skills needed after a disaster. We will cover topics related to local hazards, utility control, water storage/purification, emergency sanitation, creating emergency plans, and ways to make it through events that might disrupt your normal daily routine. 

All participants are welcome. Registration is free, and required. You do not need to bring your ticket to the training. You can register at https://bit.ly/37hI6Qi 

For questions about accessibility, or to request an accommodation, please contact Sophia Lopez at slopez@kingcounty.gov or 206-205-6545. (Requests should be made at least 14 calendar days prior to the workshop.)

Deadline to submit flood damage reports
Event description/details:
Flooding, wind, and landslides from recent winter storms have buffeted residents and businesses across King County. Those who suffered property damage or other losses since January 20, 2020 may be eligible for financial assistance. Eligibility is determined through a damage assessment process, now underway, that takes into account the total reported losses within King County.

Individuals and businesses in King County are encouraged to submit reports of losses to King County Emergency Management online at kingcounty.gov/damage or by phone at 1-800-523-5044. Deadline to submit a report is February 21. 

Submitting a report does not guarantee reimbursement. 

Damage reports are for uninsured losses. Before filing a damage report with King County, residents and business owners should contact their insurance provider about existing coverage and deductibles. They are also urged to document damage with photographs and keep records of all cleanup and repair costs.

Event Name: North Highline Subarea Plan Community Meeting
Event description/details:
The North Highline Subarea Plan will guide development in North Highline over the next 20 years. It will focus on zoning, long-term land use, and issues like housing, commercial and industrial areas, and community character. The next community meeting will be on Wednesday, Feb. 19, 5:30-6:30 p.m. in the Joe Thomas Room at KCHA-Greenbridge (9800 8th Avenue SW, Seattle). Learn about the plan and share your vision for your neighborhood. Refreshments will be provided. Language interpretation will be provided in Khmer and Vietnamese. Disability accommodations are available on request.

If you can’t attend or have more questions, King County staff members will also be available at the White Center Library (1409 SW 107th Street, Seattle) on Thursday, Feb. 20, 1-5 p.m.

Event Name: Disaster Reporting Open House
Event description/details:
King County residents and business owners who have questions about reporting property damage or other losses from the recent storms and flooding, or need help completing a report, are invited to an open house this week.

The event will take place on Thursday, February 13 from 6:30 to 8:30 p.m. at Lord of Life Lutheran Church and Community Center, 12819 160th Ave. SE in Renton. Staff from King County Emergency Management, the Department of Local Services, and other King County agencies will be on hand to talk to residents and business owners, answer questions about the disaster assistance process, and provide help in filling out the damage assessment form. Light refreshments will be provided. 

King County Emergency Management is currently collecting information regarding weather-related damage and losses suffered since January 20. If your home or business sustained damage as a result of the severe weather, you may be eligible for federal disaster assistance. Eligibility is determined through an assessment process that takes into account the total reported losses within King County. Submitting a report does not guarantee reimbursement. 

Damage reporting forms are available online at kingcounty.gov/damage. Reports can also be filed by calling 1-800-523-5044 from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. weekdays excluding holidays. Reports must be filed by February 21. 

For more information about the open house, email AskLocalServices@kingcounty.gov or call 1-800-523-5044.

Event Name: Seattle/King County Health Clinic

This four-day health clinic that runs February 13-16, 2020 provides free dental, vision, and medical care for people who struggle to access and afford healthcare.

PLEASE SHARE THIS EVENT WITH PEOPLE IN NEED.

All are welcome! Patients do not need ID or proof of immigration status. Services are not limited to residents of Seattle and King County.

Event description/details:
Join King County Parks this summer for the BECU Movies@Marymoor outdoor cinema series. Events are dog friendly and include live entertainment, food trucks, and big screen movies under the stars.

Seating opens at 6:30 p.m. Movies start at dusk. Admission is $5 cash per person or $6 credit. Kids under ages 5 and under are free.

Outside food and beverage is allowed.

For more information, visit moviesatmarymoor.com or facebook.com/moviesatmarymoor. The series is produced by Epic Events and presented by Overlake Medical Clinics.

Seating is on the grass; low-back chairs or blankets are recommended.

A $5 parking permit is required to park at Marymoor, which can be purchased from the vending machines located throughout the park.

This is a dog-friendly event. Pets must remain on a leash at all times.

There are no ATMs on site.

Event Name: National Night Out
Event description/details: National Night Out is an annual community-building campaign that promotes partnerships between law enforcement, first responders, and other government agencies and the people they all serve. The purpose of NNO is to make our neighborhoods safer, more caring places to live. This annual event, held the first Tuesday in August, enhances the relationship between neighbors and law enforcement while bringing back a true sense of community. It also provides a great opportunity to bring police and neighbors together under positive circumstances. To celebrate NNO, many neighborhoods host block parties, festivals, parades, cookouts and various other community events with safety demonstrations, seminars, youth events, visits from emergency personnel, exhibits and much, much more. National Night Out is sponsored by the National Association of Town Watch (NATW).

Event Name: Airport Master Plan Update Public Meeting
Event description/details:
After a delay, King County International Airport-Boeing Field's Master Plan Update process is again underway. Residents are invited to hear from airport director John Parrott and his team to learn more about the plan and share their views on the latest developments.

The Master Plan Update is a comprehensive study to consider how the airport should be developed to meet current and future needs. It covers future alternatives for runways, taxiways, passenger buildings, tenant leaseholds, freight handling, as well as maintenance facilities, general aviation, and other facilities.

The meeting will take place in the Arrivals Building, just south of the historic red brick Main Terminal.

Event Name: Disaster Preparedness Workshop
Event description/details:
King County is prone to many hazards, and when one happens many services we rely on will be overwhelmed. It may be difficult for residents to travel or communicate. Residents need to be prepared to be self-sufficient during these times. Understanding of disaster skills is critical to being prepared.

This workshop will provide an overview on hazards and the certain skills needed after a disaster. We will cover topics related to: local hazards, utility control, water storage/purification, emergency sanitation, creating emergency plans and ways to make it through events that might disrupt your normal daily routine.

Event Name: Charter Review Commission Community Meeting
Event description/details:
The King County Charter provides the basic long-term structure for King County government. The charter institutionalizes core values of checks and balances, accountability, and merit, and seeks to promote an effective, efficient, and responsive government. Every ten years, King County is required to review the charter. The Charter Review Commission leads this work and makes recommendations for amendments that are then presented to voters.

In order to guide this work, the CRC is conducting community outreach to collect input on how the charter might be improved or changed, which in turn could help make King County government more responsive and effective.

Please join us at one of our upcoming community meetings to share feedback on potential amendments to the King County Charter. Your feedback is important to this work. You may also submit your feedback via email at CharterReview@kingcounty.gov.

Event Name: Discovery Park Reservoir Open House
Event description/details:
Work this summer by the King County Wastewater Treatment Division (WTD) to modify an underground water reservoir in Seattle?s Discovery Park will require partial closures to portions of two hiking trails.

An open house on Feb. 23 at the Discovery Park Environmental Learning Center in Seattle will provide details of the work, which will take three to five months to complete and require partial closures along the Loop and Capehart trails.

The open house runs from 10 a.m. to noon at the learning center, 3801 Discovery Park Blvd.

King County is protecting public health with upgrades to the underground water-storage facility by providing safe and efficient access for annual inspections, and by meeting current standards for protecting water sources.

Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Celebration
Event description/details:
Now in its 32nd year, King County will again celebrate the life and legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., our county's namesake. This annual celebration recognizes the impact that Dr. King had on our community and our nation, and reminds us to keep striving toward his dream of equity and justice.

This year's program will include music, spoken word, and a keynote by Ijeoma Oluo, local New York Times bestselling author of So You Want to Talk About Race.

As a part of the 2019 celebration, county officials are inviting the public to put into words or pictures the ideas and ideals for America and the world Dr. King gave his life for. The county is looking for the public's interpretation, a photo, a work of art, or an essay, of the theme for the 2019 celebration, which is taken from a quote by Dr. King: "I believe that unarmed truth and unconditional love will have the final word in reality. "

Please submit your work via email at esj@kingcounty.gov.

Event Name: Lower Green River Flood Management Plan Public Meeting
Event description/details: The King County Flood Control District is preparing a Lower Green River Corridor Flood Hazard Management Plan for approximately 21 river miles of the Lower Green River that flow through the cities of Auburn, Kent, Renton, Tukwila, and unincorporated King County. The goal of the Plan is to provide a long-term approach to reduce flood risk and improve fish habitat while supporting the economic prosperity of the region. A public scoping meeting will be held in January to share information with members of the public and solicit feedback on the plan.?
